    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-04-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-04-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="1241"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1241">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72111/2042</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The British Ambassador</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SRSCA1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Spring Rice</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the</hi>
                    <gloss type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Secretary of State</hi>
                    </gloss>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-04-19">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 19, 1915</hi>.</date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received April 21</hi>.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: With further reference to your
                    letter of April 16 I beg to advise you of the result of the enquiries I have
                    made in regard to the reported action of the British crusier <hi rend="italic"
                        >Suffolk</hi> in communicating with the shore through tugs and by
                    radiotelegraphy with other vessels. The Admiral informs me that strict regard is
                    being paid to the neutrality of the United States. The only incident which may
                    have given rise to the report is that in which, on one occasion, an
                    outward-bound merchant vessel handed a gift of newspapers to H.M.S. <hi
                        rend="italic">Suffolk’s</hi> boat. The British Vice Consul at Norfolk has
                    made extensive enquiries by my instructions and has failed to trace any other
                    instance where there has been communication with the <hi rend="italic"
                        >Suffolk</hi>.</p>
                <p>The Admiral states categorically that no communication of any kind by wireless
                    telegraphy has passed between the <hi rend="italic">Suffolk</hi> and any other
                    merchant vessel, or the shore.</p>
                <p>I trust this report will satisfy the United States authorities that scrupulous
                    care is being taken to observe the obligations of international law.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SRSCA1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cecil Spring Rice</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
